1) Problem statement¶

Your given goal and problem statement for the analysis of your given dataset

  • Goal: - To understand the distribution (including summary statistics and whether they are normally distributed) and inter-relatedness of, in particular, the group-level and individual-level social network analysis metrics. - Continue with above with the messaging frequency metrics. - Feature engineering (10 features with 5 using network columns).

  • Background: The project is related to determining whether the other columns have a impact on the target variables O:E and hour_of_discharge (Observed to expected length of stay in the hospital)

3) Pre-process Data¶

3.1) Selecting only required features from the dataset¶

There Are three kinds of analysis the we are going to incorporate in this analysis to answer the goal of our problem defination.

  • First we will use the given features above in .rtf file to check the effect of features on O:E and hour of discharge.

    • Select these features from the dataset
    • Checking for any missing or null values
    • Explore the relationship of these features with "O:E" and "hour_of_discharge" variables.

  • Secondly, We will check answers related to communication metrics what impact does communication metrics have on the O:E and hour of discharge.

    • we will use sent_msgs_per_day and read_msgs_per_day
  • Thirdly, We are going to create the network of patients
    • compute the size of network
      • number of nodes, number of edges
      • density
      • Average degree
      • Clustering coefficient
  • Finally we will compute the centrality measures in our network to find
    • Indegree measures of the network
    • Outdegree mesures of the network

4.6) Impact O:E and hour and discharge by discharge on weekend feature¶

In [676]:
from collections import Counter
### Checking The impact of above features on the O:E


def get_lists(oe):
   
    ls1, ls2 = list(),list()
    for val in oe:
        dat = problem1_data[problem1_data["O:E"] == val]["discharge_on_weekend"]
        dict_Data = dict(Counter(dat))


        if(len(dict_Data)>1):
            ls1.append(dict_Data[0])
            ls2.append(dict_Data[1])
        elif(len(dict_Data) == 1):
            ls1.append(dict_Data[0])
            ls2.append(0)
        else:
            ls1.append(0)
            ls2.append(0)
            
    return ls1, ls2
        


oe = set(problem1_data["O:E"])
ls1, ls2 = get_lists(oe)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2 , figsize = (18,5))
        
ax[0].bar([val-0.1 for val in oe], ls1, width=0.3, label = "discharge_on_weekend = 0")
ax[0].bar([val+0.2 for val in oe], ls2, width=0.3, label = "discharge_on_weekend = 1")
ax[0].set_title("The impact on O:E using discharge on weekend feature")
ax[0].legend()


oe = set(problem1_data["hour_of_discharge"])
ls1, ls2 = get_lists(oe)

ax[1].bar([val-0.1 for val in oe], ls1, width=0.3, label = "discharge_on_weekend = 0")
ax[1].bar([val+0.2 for val in oe], ls2, width=0.3, label = "discharge_on_weekend = 1")
ax[1].set_title("The impact on hour of discharge using discharge on weekend feature")
ax[1].legend()

plt.show()

Explainations:¶

The analysis reveals the influence of weekend discharges on both O:E (Observed-to-Expected) and hour of discharge values. It's evident that the majority of patients are not being discharged during weekends. There's a limited number of cases where patients are discharged with O:E values of 0 and 1, while no other O:E values indicate discharges on weekends.

The pattern is also reflected in the hour of discharge values, with a small number of patients being discharged when the hour of discharge is less than 5.

5.1) Impact of Avg_DBP on O:E and Hour of discharge¶

In [804]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (16,8))
sns.boxplot(x="O:E", y="avg_dbp", data=clinical_measure_data,ax=ax[0])
ax[0].set_title("Average dbp for O:E")
sns.boxplot(x="hour_of_discharge", y="avg_dbp", data=clinical_measure_data,ax=ax[1])
ax[1].set_title("Average dbp for hour_of_discharge")
ax[1].set_xticklabels(ax[1].get_xticklabels(), rotation=45) 
plt.show()

Explainations:¶

In the box plots shown above, it's clear that we can evaluate the influence of mean diastolic blood pressure (DBP) during a patient's stay on different O:E (Observed-to-Expected) values.

An intriguing pattern emerges when examining the average DBP values. While the average diastolic blood pressure (DBP) generally falls within the range of 60 to 80, we notice that for a more extended stay (specifically at 6), the mean SBP value rises above 80. This observation suggests that elevated mean DBP might be a contributing factor to patients' longer hospital stays.

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2 , figsize = (18,5))

def get_lists(var,dat):
    ls = []
    ls2 = []
    
    for val in dat:
        counter =communication_data[communication_data[var] == val]
        ls.append(sum(counter.sent_msgs_per_day))
        ls2.append(sum(counter.read_msgs_per_day))
    
    return ls, ls2
    

dat = set(communication_data["O:E"])
ls , ls2 = get_lists("O:E",dat)

ax[0].bar([val-0.1 for val in dat], ls, width=0.3, label = "sent_messages")
ax[0].bar([val+0.2 for val in dat], ls2, width=0.3, label = "read_messages")
ax[0].set_title("The number of read and sent messages for O:E")
ax[0].legend()


dat = set(communication_data["hour_of_discharge"])
ls , ls2 = get_lists("hour_of_discharge", dat)


ax[1].bar([val-0.1 for val in dat], ls, width=0.3, label = "sent_messages")
ax[1].bar([val+0.2 for val in dat], ls2, width=0.3, label = "read_messages")
ax[1].set_title("The number of read and sent messages for hour_of_discharge")
ax[1].legend()


plt.show()

explainations:¶

Based on the visualizations presented above, there is a notable imbalance in the number of received messages compared to the sent messages of O:E when O:E is less than 2. A similar pattern emerges in the context of hour of discharge, but with a difference: when the hour of discharge value exceeds 10, there is an observable increase in the volume of communication metrics.

7.1) Converting The raw network data into Graph representations:¶

For creating the network from raw data we will use encounter index and patient index feature from the dataset.

In [601]:
### Making bipartite network:

G = nx.Graph()
for i in range(len(Network_data)):
    
    node1 = Network_data.patient_index[i]
    node2 = Network_data.Encounter_index[i]
    
    if(G.has_edge(node1, node2)):
        continue
    else:
        if(node1 == node2):
            continue
        G.add_edge(node1, node2)

import matplotlib.colors as mcolors
import matplotlib.cm as cmx

def draw_clu(G, pos, measures):
    
    clusters= list(set(measures.values()))
    
    colors = ["blue", "red", "green", "purple", "yellow"]
    
    
    unique_colors = dict()
    for val in range(len(val_lis)):
        unique_colors[val_lis[val]] = colors[val] 

    colors = dict()
    for val in measures:
        colors[val] = unique_colors[measures[val]]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    # Create the plot of the network to be placed in the figure
    
    nodes = nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos,node_size=20,
                                   #cmap=mcolors.ListedColormap(plt.cm.Set3(clusters)), 
                                   node_color=list(colors.values()),
                                   nodelist=list(measures.keys()))

    # Add edges to the plot
    edges = nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos,width=0.3)
    
    
    plt.title("Inteconnected groups of patient indexs")
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

explainations:¶

The indegree plot illustrates the number of incoming connections to the Medicine Attending. Notably, there's a substantial concentration of patient indexes associated with an indegree value of 2. This suggests that a large portion of patient IDs receive relatively fewer incoming connections from Medicine Attending, while only a select few patient indexes receive a high volume of incoming connections from Medicine Attending.

This pattern is mirrored in the outdegree plot, where a significant number of patients actively send outgoing connections to Medicine Attending, indicating their active communication.

8.3) Impact of Nurse indegree and Nurse outdegree on O:E¶

In [824]:
fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,1, figsize=(15, 10))
oe = set(centrality_data["O:E"])

for val in oe:
    filterd =centrality_data[centrality_data["O:E"] == val]
    group =filterd.groupby("Nurse_indegree")["O:E"].count()
    ax[0].plot(group, label = f"O:E = {val}" )

ax[0].legend()

hod = set(centrality_data["O:E"])
for val in hod:
    filterd =centrality_data[centrality_data["O:E"] == val]
    group =filterd.groupby("Nurse_outdegree")["O:E"].count()
    ax[1].plot(group, label = f"O:E = {val}" )
    
ax[1].legend()
plt.show()

Explaintions:¶

The noticeable pattern of higher Nurse Indegree values for O:E values at 0 and 1 can be attributed to the substantial number of patient indexes who have short hospital stays of 0 and 1 day. This pattern aligns with the idea that when patients stay for such a brief duration, there is likely to be a higher volume of nurse interactions and connections, resulting in the observed higher Nurse Indegree values for these specific O:E categories compared to other O:E values.
